sections.content:
124.  No public officer shall be compelled to disclose communications 
made  to  him  in  official  confidence  when  he  considers  that  the 
public  interest  would  suffer  by  the  disclosure:

(c)  the questions are improper if there is a great disproportion 
between the importance of the imputation made against 
the witness’s character and the importance of his evidence;

(a)  by the evidence of persons who testify that they from their 
knowledge  of  the  witness  believe  him  to  be  unworthy 
of  credit;

(b)  by proof that the witness has been bribed, or has accepted 
the  offer  of  a  bribe,  or  has  received  any  other  corrupt 
inducement  to  give  his  evidence;
